<TITLE> India sets new talks with allies on nuclear deal </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 NEW DELHI, Oct 22 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - India's government and communist parties will hold their next meeting over a controversial nuclear deal with the United States on Nov. 16, Foreign Minister Pranab Mukherjee said on Monday. The decision came after a meeting with the government and its communist allies, who oppose the deal. The four main left parties which prop up Prime Minister Manmohan Singh's coalition had threatened to end support if the deal was pursued, forcing the government to signal it would give in this month after weeks of sabre rattling. The civilian nuclear cooperation deal aims to lift a three-decade ban on sales of US nuclear fuel and reactors to India, imposed after it conducted a nuclear test in 1974 while staying out of non-proliferation agreemen
